Looking at the mutation, the change is from `i < length` to `i <= length` in the first loop that copies arguments into the `args` array. This means when `pull` is called with a function of arity 1 (creating a partial sink), the mutated code will try to access `arguments[length]` which is `undefined`, adding an extra `undefined` element to the `args` array.

This extra `undefined` will cause issues when the partial sink is later called - specifically, when it tries to pipe through the streams, it will pass `undefined` as one of the arguments to `pull`, which will then try to call `undefined` as a function or access properties on it.

Let me trace through the behavior:
- Original: `args` has exactly `length` elements (the actual arguments)
- Mutated: `args` has `length + 1` elements, with the last being `undefined`

When the partial sink is invoked with a `read` function, it will call `pull(read, ref[0], ref[1], ...)` where one of the refs is `undefined`. This will cause an error when trying to call `undefined` as a function.

